<% meth="subset_table" %>
<div class="lvl1">

	
	<p> This binary is used to get a subset from the input table, starting from row X and taking Y rows from there. </p>
	<h3> Basic example </h3>
		<p> La tabla de entrada se indica con el flag -i. La fila por la que se empieza con el flag -s o --start_line (indice basado en 1) 
		y la cantidad de filas que se extraen desde ese punto con el flag -l o --lines_to_subset. Además, si la tabla original tiene un
		header y se quiere mantener en la tabla subseteada, se puede utilizar el flag -H o --header  </p>
		<p> The input table is specified with the -i flag. The row were we'll start subsetting our table and the number of rows we want to extract from that point will be specified with the --offset flag (1 based), separating both numbers by a comma. We can also add the -H or --header flag.</p>
		<p> In this case, we'll get 4 rows from the metrics table, starting from row 3 and keeping the header. </p>
		<%
			table_name = 'metrics_table'
			args = f"-i tables/{table_name} --offset 3,4 -H"
		%>
		${show_n_exec(table_name, args, "cmdtabs")}


	<h3> Subsetting the whole table in different files with K lines per file. </h3>
		<p> If we want to subset the table in different files, each one containing K number of lines, we can use the --sp_chunk_size flag, indicating the number of lines we want per file, keeping in mind that we will also need to add the --split_out flag. The -o flag is used to state the ouput directory where the files will be stored. </p>
		<p> In this case, we'll separate the disease clusters table in different files, each one of them containing 4 lines (we'll see that the last one only has 2 due to the input table having 10 entries). </p>
		<%
			table_name = 'disease_cluster_ref_rnd'
			args = f"-i tables/{table_name} --split_out --sp_chunk_size 4 -o outputs/subset_table"
			output_table = 'outputs/subset_table/*'
		%>
		${show_n_exec(table_name, args, "cmdtabs", out=output_table)}


	<h3> Subsetting the whole table in N different files with the same number of entries in each one </h3>
		<p> Si se quiere partir la tabla en una cantidad fija de N archivos , cada uno de ellos con la misma cantidad de registros, se puede utilizar el flag -n o --number_of_files en vez de los flags -s y -l o --chunk_size. En este caso el flag de output -o también indica la carpeta donde se guardarán los archivos. </p>
		<p> If we want to subset the table in a fixed number of N files, each one of them containing the same number of entries, we can use the --sp_file_number flag, indicating the number of files you want. Just like before, we will also have to add the --split_out flag. The -o output flag will also indicated where we will store the files. </p>
		
		<p> In this case, we will separate the disease clusters table in 2 files. </p>
		<%
			table_name = 'disease_cluster_ref_rnd'
			args = f"-i tables/{table_name} --split_out --sp_file_number 2 -o outputs/subset_table2"
			output_table2 = 'outputs/subset_table2/*'
		%>
		${show_n_exec(table_name, args, "cmdtabs", out=output_table2)}

</div>